The defendant Taneesha R Dorsey was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer in court, defendant Taneesha R Dorsey not in court, in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Victim appears; additional statements made regarding restitution.  Restitution increased an additional $150.00 to cover the loss of victim's cell phone.

Attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer in court, defendant Taneesha R Dorsey not in court, in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Victim here.   ADA Arn informed the Court that the victim, Curtis G., has filed a complaint against him with the Police and Fire Commission.  Another ADA to handle this matter.   Statement by Curtis G.  Court sets restitution at $3,400.00 to be paid in monthly increments of $100.00 per month by the defendant commencing June 1, 2016.  If defendant misses a payment, the total amount of restitution still due and owing will convert to a civil judgment.  Court wants 25% of canteen account to go towards restitution.  Court is unsure if this is a proper procedure.  Determination will be made prior to the next court date if this is proper.  Also, it has to be determined who the recipient of the restitution should be as Title 19 bought the property that was damaged and will not replace the damaged property.  Parties to determine who the restitution payments should be sent to.  Matter set for continued restitution hearing.  Restitution hearing scheduled for October 29, 2015 at 01:30 pm.

Defendant Taneesha R Dorsey in court with attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties request an adjournment of the currently scheduled Restitution Hearing.  Medicare may reimburse victim for his losses.  Restitution hearing scheduled for October 2, 2015 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Taneesha R Dorsey not in court, in custody. Attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer in court. Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court in trial.  Restitution hearing scheduled for August 11, 2015 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Taneesha R Dorsey in court with attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer.  Defendant Taneesha R Dorsey in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.
Sentencing proceeded:  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.  Additional statements by Curtis G and Alonzo D.  

The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 6 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 4 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 2 YEARS, consecutive to any other sentence, credit for 82 days.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 4 YEARS with the following conditions:

Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
-Restitution set at to Curtis G. subject to modification after the scheduled restitution hearing
-Court costs and victim/witness surcharges are to be paid during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge during term of probation;  nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment.
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
-No association with drug users, drug houses and drug dealers
-Mental health assessment and any recommended treatment to include any counseling, therapy and taking any prescribed medications
-Obtain/maintain employment
-Obtain GED or HSED 
-No contact with Curtis G.
-Defendant is not eligible for Dosage probation
-As a condition of probation, Court ordered defendant serve 10 MONTHS in the House of Corrections, with release to Day Reporting Center.   No good time credit; no electric monitoring 

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms or body armor; also he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been restored.
